04223nam a22006255i 9780812295337DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122953377 a10.9783/97808122953372doi  a(DE-B1597)521535  a(OCoLC)1051770857  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360402bisacsh1 aHeerman, M. Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Alchemy of Slavery :bHuman Bondage and Emancipation in the Illinois Country, 1730-1865 /cM. Scott Heerman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerica in the Nineteenth Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Slavery and Freedom on the American Continent -- tChapter 1. Making the French Negroes -- tChapter 2. Another Law and Empire -- tChapter 3. Remaking the French Negroes -- tChapter 4. Contesting Bondage in the Slave North -- tChapter 5. Paths to Independence -- tChapter 6. Freedom Practices, Freedom Politics -- tConclusion. North of Slavery, South of Freedom -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this sweeping saga that spans empires, peoples, and nations, M. Scott Heerman chronicles the long history of slavery in the heart of the continent and traces its many iterations through law and social practice. Arguing that slavery had no fixed institutional form, Heerman traces practices of slavery through indigenous, French, and finally U.S. systems of captivity, inheritable slavery, lifelong indentureship, and the kidnapping of free people. By connecting the history of indigenous bondage to that of slavery and emancipation in the Atlantic world, Heerman shows how French, Spanish, and Native North American practices shaped the history of slavery in the United States.The Alchemy of Slavery foregrounds the diverse and adaptable slaving practices that masters deployed to build a slave economy in the Upper Mississippi River Valley, attempting to outmaneuver their antislavery opponents. In time, a formidable cast of lawyers and antislavery activists set their sights on ending slavery in Illinois. Abraham Lincoln, Lyman Trumbull, Richard Yates, and many other future leaders of the Republican party partnered with African Americans to wage an extended campaign against slavery in the region. Across a century and a half, slavery's nearly perpetual reinvention takes center stage: masters turning Indian captives into slaves, slaves into servants, former slaves into kidnapping victims; and enslaved people turning themselves into free men and women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Frontlist Package 2019z978311065205540uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229533740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812295337423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812295337.jpg  a978-3-11-065205-5  Penn Press eBook Frontlist Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK